What YOU need to do manually (one-time, via AWS Console with SSO):
Create IAM Role named sap-hana-backup-role with path /sap/

Trust: EC2, Backup, SSM services
Attach these 6 policies:
AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore
AWSBackupDataTransferAccess
AWSBackupFullAccess
AWSBackupRestoreAccessForSAPHANA
AWSBackupServiceRolePolicyForBackup
AWSSystemsManagerForSAPFullAccess
Also attach a policy allowing secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on your POC-SAP-Hanna secret
Create Instance Profile named sap-hana-backup-role-instance-profile

Add the role sap-hana-backup-role to it
After creating those, re-run the pipeline.


When you create the IAM role sap-hana-backup-role in AWS Console, you attach 6 managed policies (the ones I listed). But your SAP HANA EC2 instances also need to read the secret POC-SAP-Hanna from Secrets Manager during the SAP registration step.

So on the same role (sap-hana-backup-role), add one more inline policy:

Steps:

Go to IAM → Roles → sap-hana-backup-role
Click Add permissions → Create inline policy
Switch to JSON tab
Paste this:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "secretsmanager:GetSecretValue",
        "secretsmanager:DescribeSecret"
      ],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-1:677277859823:secret:POC-SAP-Hanna*"
    }
  ]
}
Click Next → Name it allow-read-sap-hanna-secret → Create policy
Why? When the SSM document runs on EC2 instances, it executes:

aws secretsmanager get-secret-value --secret-id POC-SAP-Hanna
The EC2 instance uses the sap-hana-backup-role role. Without this policy, it will get "Access Denied" when trying to read the password.


